Embedded Nerd Design System v3.0
Chapter 0 — Philosophy & Core Principles
0.1 Purpose

Embedded Nerd exists to create the highest quality embedded systems tutorials on the web.

Every article should help readers understand a concept, build a real project and gain confidence working with electronics.

The objective is not simply to publish content, but to become a trusted technical reference for beginners, students, makers and professional engineers.

Every tutorial must provide real value.

If a section does not improve the reader's understanding, it should not be included.

0.2 Mission

Embedded Nerd aims to make embedded systems easier to learn through practical, well-structured and visually consistent tutorials.

Every project should be reproducible by readers using affordable hardware and freely available software whenever possible.

The website should become a long-term educational resource rather than a collection of disconnected articles.

0.3 Vision

The long-term goal is to become one of the world's leading educational websites for:

Arduino
ESP32
Raspberry Pi
STM32
RP2040
Embedded Linux
Sensors
Displays
IoT
Electronics
Communication Protocols
Robotics

Every article published should strengthen this vision.

0.4 Audience

The primary audience includes:

Beginners
Students
Hobbyists
Makers
Engineers
Teachers
DIY enthusiasts

Articles should assume curiosity rather than expertise.

Avoid unnecessary jargon.

Whenever a technical term is introduced, explain it.

0.5 Educational Philosophy

Readers should never need to search another website to complete the project.

Every tutorial should contain everything necessary to reproduce the results.

Include:

explanation
wiring
code
troubleshooting
expected output
common mistakes
FAQs
useful references

A complete article is always better than a short article.

0.6 Writing Principles

Writing should be:

Professional
Friendly
Technical
Concise
Practical

Avoid:

marketing language
exaggerated claims
clickbait
filler
repetition

Every paragraph should teach something useful.

0.7 Technical Accuracy

Technical correctness always has higher priority than SEO.

Never publish:

untested code
incorrect wiring
unrealistic examples
fake screenshots
fake Serial Monitor output

If information cannot be verified, clearly state any assumptions.

0.8 Code Philosophy

Every code example must:

Compile successfully.

Be properly commented.

Use meaningful variable names.

Follow Arduino coding conventions.

Avoid unnecessary complexity.

Prefer readability over cleverness.

Readers should be able to copy, compile and upload the code without modification.

0.9 Image Philosophy

Images exist to teach.

Every image should improve understanding.

Avoid decorative graphics that add no educational value.

Images must:

be clean
be consistent
use realistic hardware
have a white background
include the Embedded Nerd logo
use professional typography

The same visual identity must be maintained across every article.

0.10 Consistency

Every article should feel like it was written by the same author.

Readers should instantly recognize:

writing style
layout
images
diagrams
tables
code formatting

Consistency builds trust.

0.11 Simplicity

Simple explanations are preferred over complex explanations.

If a beginner can understand a concept, experienced readers will also understand it.

Never explain something in a complicated way just to sound technical.

0.12 Practical Learning

Every article should help readers build something real.

Whenever possible include:

complete projects
practical examples
real-world applications
troubleshooting
improvements
next steps

Readers should finish every tutorial having learned something they can immediately apply.

0.13 Evergreen Content

Content should remain useful for many years.

Avoid unnecessary references to dates, trends or temporary software versions unless they are essential.

Whenever possible, write tutorials that will still be relevant five years from now.

0.14 SEO Philosophy

SEO exists to help people discover useful content.

It should never reduce readability.

Write for humans first.

Optimize for search engines second.

Natural language always takes priority over keyword density.

0.15 Monetization Philosophy

Affiliate links should help readers find the correct hardware.

They should never interrupt learning.

Educational value always comes before monetization.

A reader who trusts the content is far more valuable than a short-term affiliate click.

0.16 Community

Embedded Nerd encourages experimentation.

Readers should feel comfortable modifying the code and improving projects.

Whenever appropriate, encourage readers to:

experiment
modify parameters
build improvements
share results
contribute on GitHub

Learning continues after the article ends.

0.17 Continuous Improvement

Every article is a living document.

If better code, improved diagrams or clearer explanations become available, update the article.

Quality is more important than publication speed.

0.18 Final Principle

Every article published on Embedded Nerd should make readers think:

"This is the best tutorial I've found on this topic."

If the article does not achieve this standard, continue improving it before publication.


