6.3 Universal Style Prompt

Use this style as the base for all images:

Create a clean, professional technical illustration on a white background using realistic electronic components, soft shadows, modern sans-serif typography, subtle green (#10B981) highlights, consistent spacing, and a minimalist educational layout. Place the official Embedded Nerd logo in the top-right corner with appropriate margin and add EmbeddedNerd.com subtly in the bottom-right corner. The image should resemble a page from a modern electronics textbook rather than a marketing graphic.

6.4 Hero Image Prompt

Purpose

Create an attractive cover image for the article.

Standard Prompt

Create a professional hero image (1200×630 px) with a white background, showing the main hardware used in the tutorial arranged neatly. Display the article title prominently using modern typography. Add soft shadows, green highlights, realistic electronic components, the official Embedded Nerd logo in the top-right corner, and EmbeddedNerd.com in the bottom-right corner. The design should be clean, balanced and suitable for Open Graph social sharing.

6.5 Wiring Diagram Prompt

Purpose

Show physical connections.

Standard Prompt

Create a professional wiring diagram (1600×900 px) showing realistic development boards and modules connected using coloured jumper wires. Use red for VCC, black for GND, green for SDA, blue for SCL, orange for MOSI, purple for MISO, yellow for SCK, grey for CS, cyan for TX and magenta for RX. Label every pin clearly using modern typography. Use a white background with subtle green highlights and include the official Embedded Nerd logo.

6.6 Pinout Prompt

Purpose

Show all important pins.

Standard Prompt

Create a clean pinout diagram (1600×900 px) showing the board from a top-down view with every important pin labelled using the official manufacturer names. Use colour coding for power, ground, communication and GPIO pins. Keep the background white and the design simple, clear and suitable for beginners.

6.7 Flow Diagram Prompt

Purpose

Explain program execution.

Standard Prompt

Create a modern flowchart (1600×900 px) using rounded rectangles, green accent colours, clean arrows and minimal text. The background should be white with generous spacing. The diagram should be understandable within a few seconds and suitable for a beginner electronics tutorial.

6.8 Serial Monitor Prompt

Purpose

Display realistic output.

Standard Prompt

Create a realistic Serial Monitor screenshot showing clean monospaced text with believable sensor readings. Do not invent unrealistic values. Keep the layout similar to the Arduino IDE Serial Monitor. The screenshot should be sharp and easy to read.

6.9 Logic Analyzer Prompt

Purpose

Explain digital communication.

Standard Prompt

Create a realistic logic analyzer screenshot showing digital waveforms with labelled channels and protocol decoding where applicable. Use a clean white interface with readable timing information suitable for educational documentation.

6.10 Oscilloscope Prompt

Purpose

Show analog or digital waveforms.

Standard Prompt

Create a realistic oscilloscope screenshot showing a clean waveform with labelled voltage and time scales. The image should resemble a modern digital oscilloscope and be easy to understand.

6.11 Finished Project Prompt

Purpose

Show the completed build.

Standard Prompt

Create a high-quality photograph-style illustration of the completed electronics project assembled on a clean workbench. Use organised wiring, realistic components, natural lighting and a neutral background. Include subtle Embedded Nerd branding without distracting from the project.

6.12 PCB Prompt

Purpose

Show printed circuit boards.

Standard Prompt

Create a realistic top-view rendering of a professionally designed PCB with clearly labelled components, solder mask, silkscreen and mounting holes. Maintain a clean educational presentation on a white background.

6.13 Comparison Prompt

Purpose

Compare two boards or modules.

Standard Prompt

Create a side-by-side comparison image with both boards shown at the same scale. Present specifications in a clean comparison table below the boards. Use green highlights for advantages and maintain the Embedded Nerd visual style.

